Game Plan¶

We will first do some simple EDA and conversion in order for us to have our first submission to Kaggle quickly to establish a baseline.

We will then do further EDA and further model building to produce more enhanced submissions.

Contents¶

  1. Simple EDA
  2. Data Cleaning
  3. Linear Models
  4. First Submission as Baseline
  5. Further EDA and Transformation
  6. Feature Selection and Retraining

In [87]:
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_log_error
import math

def rmsle_calc(y_true, y_pred, **kwargs):
    y_pred_exp = list(np.exp(y_pred))
    y_true_exp = list(np.exp(y_true))
    
    return math.sqrt(mean_squared_log_error(y_pred_exp, y_true_exp)) # somehow mean_squared_log_error() doesn't recognize the "squared=False" argument
    
    
exp_rmsle = make_scorer(rmsle_calc, greater_is_better=False) 

scores = cross_val_score(linear_reg_log_y, X_train_num_var, Y_train_log, cv=5, scoring=exp_rmsle)
print("Linear regression with log(Y): %0.4f RMSLE score after taking exponential, with a standard deviation of %0.4f" % (scores.mean(), scores.std()))

Linear regression with log(Y): -0.1558 RMSLE score after taking exponential, with a standard deviation of 0.0269

train_with_ord_enc = train[cat_var+['SalePrice']].copy()
test_with_ord_enc = test[cat_var].copy()


def ordinal_encode(df, col):
    idx_names = df.groupby(col).median().sort_values('SalePrice').index
    temp_list = list(zip(idx_names, range(1, 1+len(idx_names))))
    order_dict = {k[0] : k[1] for k in temp_list}
    
    for key, val in order_dict.items():
        train_with_ord_enc.loc[train_with_ord_enc[col] == key, col+'_E'] = val
        test_with_ord_enc.loc[test_with_ord_enc[col] == key, col+'_E'] = val
        
    train_with_ord_enc[col+'_E'] = train_with_ord_enc[col+'_E'].astype(int)
    #there is one MSSubClass in the test set but not in the train set, so as a general fix, we fill it with median
    test_with_ord_enc[col+'_E'] = test_with_ord_enc[col+'_E'].fillna(test_with_ord_enc[col+'_E'].median()).astype(int)
    
    
for col in cat_var:
    ordinal_encode(train_with_ord_enc, col)
    
train_with_ord_enc.drop(cat_var+['SalePrice'], axis=1, inplace=True)
test_with_ord_enc.drop(cat_var, axis=1, inplace=True)

Feature Agglomeration¶

In [123]:
from sklearn.cluster import FeatureAgglomeration


from sklearn import preprocessing
scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit(X_train_transformed)
X_train_transformed_scaled = scaler.transform(X_train_transformed)


lasso_reg = linear_model.LassoLarsCV(max_iter=1000)
best_rmsle = -1
best_cluster = 0

for i in range(30, X_train_transformed.shape[1], 2):
    
    agglo = FeatureAgglomeration(n_clusters=i)
    agglo.fit(X_train_transformed_scaled)
    X_train_transformed_scaled_agglo = agglo.transform(X_train_transformed_scaled)

    scores = cross_val_score(lasso_reg, X_train_transformed_scaled_agglo, Y_train_transformed, cv=5, scoring=exp_rmsle)
    
    if scores.mean() > best_rmsle:
        best_rmsle = scores.mean() 
        best_cluster = i
    print('For cluster=', i, ". Lasso RMSLE: %0.4f RMSLE score with a SD of %0.4f" % (scores.mean(), scores.std()))

print('best no of clusters: ', best_cluster)
